                            <comment id="14480816" author="paulk" created="Thu, 2 Apr 2015 18:56:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;We&apos;ll have to double check the grammar. In the meantime, as a workaround, the non-slashy GString and the dollar slashy string both don&apos;t seem to have this problem.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;assert&lt;/span&gt; Eval.me(&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;&apos;&apos;def foo=&apos;&lt;/span&gt;bar&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;; &lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&quot;$foo*baz&quot;&lt;/span&gt;&apos;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;&apos;) == &apos;&lt;/span&gt;bar*baz&apos;
&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;assert&lt;/span&gt; Eval.me(&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;&apos;&apos;def foo=&apos;&lt;/span&gt;bar&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;; $/$foo*baz/$&apos;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;&apos;) == &apos;&lt;/span&gt;bar*baz&apos;
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14480821" author="paulk" created="Thu, 2 Apr 2015 19:20:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Looking at the grammar, it does look like a bug to me unless there is some history I am unaware of. There is a guard in the grammar (&lt;tt&gt;atValidDollarEscape&lt;/tt&gt;) that looks like it steps over an optional &apos;*&apos; but then the rules which use this guard don&apos;t seem to know about this possibility. Perhaps, a long time ago, there was someone trying to support some kind of spread within a GString placeholder, e.g. &lt;tt&gt;$*someList&lt;/tt&gt; but it was never finished or was removed but not fully.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14499129" author="paulk" created="Fri, 17 Apr 2015 02:01:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;OK, found out what the &apos;&amp;#42;&apos; handling was all about. If you have &lt;tt&gt;/&amp;#42; some comment &amp;#42;/&lt;/tt&gt; or an empty comment &lt;tt&gt;/&amp;#42;&amp;#42;/&lt;/tt&gt;, they will be treated as comments not GStrings. So in your case, the &apos;&amp;#42;&apos; isn&apos;t part of a comment but is being matched by the rules sniffing for comments. We should no doubt tweak the grammar to handle that case correctly.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14547858" author="paulk" created="Mon, 18 May 2015 10:50:40 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Another interesting snippet from here:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://marc.info/?l=groovy-scm&amp;amp;m=118311049022736&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://marc.info/?l=groovy-scm&amp;amp;m=118311049022736&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Relevant piece:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;o Spread argument directly in GStrings removed
        def bar = [1,2,3]
        def g = &quot;foo$*bar&quot;
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So indeed, &apos;$*&apos; was supported pre June 2007&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
